## The library in action

Here's the rendered look of the four primitives composed together (static HTML preview — in your app
these would be the components above):

<CodeBlock
	playground
	filename="library-demo.html"
	code={`<div class="space-y-4">
  <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Deployment</h3>
      <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-emerald-100 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-emerald-700">live</span>
      <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-amber-100 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-amber-700">staging</span>
    </div>
    <div role="alert" class="mt-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-sky-300 bg-sky-50 p-4 text-sm text-sky-800">
      A new version is available.
    </div>
    <div class="mt-4 flex gap-2">
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-indigo-600 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-white hover:bg-indigo-700">Deploy</button>
      <button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-slate-100 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-slate-900 hover:bg-slate-200">Cancel</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>`}
/>

<Callout type="insight" title="A library is a set of decisions you stop re-making">

What makes this a *library* rather than four files is **consistency of contract**: every component
takes a `class` override merged with `cn()`, every variant is a typed union, every tone draws from
the same palette logic. A consumer learns the pattern once and predicts the rest. That predictability
is the entire value proposition — your teammates stop deciding how a badge should look and start
*using* the badge. When you design components, optimise for "obvious and uniform" over "clever." The
best component library is the one nobody has to think about.

</Callout>

<Callout type="tip" title="Barrel-export for ergonomics">

Re-export your primitives from `$lib/components/ui/index.ts` so consumers write
`import { Button, Badge, Card, Alert } from '$lib/components/ui'`. Small touches like this make a
library feel finished.

</Callout>

## Knowledge check

<Quiz
	question="What single contract should every component in the library share?"
	options={[
		{ text: 'A fixed width', correct: false },
		{ text: 'A `class` prop merged via cn() plus typed variant props', correct: true },
		{ text: 'An internal store', correct: false },
		{ text: 'A hard-coded colour', correct: false }
	]}
	explanation="Uniform contracts — cn() overrides + typed variants — are what turn separate components into a coherent library."
/>

## Recap & module wrap-up

Module 7 complete. You've resolved the "utilities are repetitive" question for good: extract
components, reach for `@apply` only when you must, compose with `cn()`, and expose typed variants —
then package them as a consistent library.

Next module: **Animation & Interactivity** — bringing your components to life with tasteful motion.
